<h4> Notes: </h4>
<ul>=20
 <li>
The square root calculator provides the principal square root (the positive=
 square root which is most commonly used). &nbsp;
Multiplying the principal square root by -1 will provide the negative squar=
e root if needed.
 </li> =20
 <li>The square root of a negative number results in an imaginary number no=
ted by the letter "i".=20
 </li>
</ul>

<a name=3D"definition"> </a>


<br>

<h3> Square Root: </h3>
<p> The square root of a number is a value that when multiplied by itself e=
quals the original number. &nbsp; =20
 <em>Example</em>: &nbsp; The square root of 9 =3D 3. &nbsp;  Thus:  3 x 3 =
=3D 9. </p>=20

<br>
<p><span class=3D"lightgrey"> Where A and B are valid numbers:</span><br>
A is the square root of B if: &nbsp; A x A =3D B


</p>




<a name=3D"symbol"> </a>

<br>
<ul>
<li>
<h4> Square Root Symbol / Square Root Sign: </h4>
<p> The square root of a number N is commonly represented by:  &nbsp; =20
<span style=3D"white-space: nowrap; font-size:larger">
=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">&nbsp;N &nbsp;</span>
</span>=20

<br> It can also be represented by: &nbsp; =20
<span style=3D"white-space: nowrap; font-size:larger">
<sup>2</sup>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">&nbsp;N &nbs=
p;</span>
</span>
<br> In exponential notation, it can be represented by: &nbsp; N<sup>1/2</s=
up>=20
<br>  "Square root" can be abbreviated as  "sqrt" &nbsp; <em>Example</em>: =
&nbsp; sqrt(2) =3D 1.4142136

<br>
<br>  Thus all of the following are equivalent:=20
<br>


Square Root of N &nbsp; =3D=20
&nbsp;=20

<span style=3D"white-space: nowrap; font-size:larger">
=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">&nbsp;N &nbsp;</span>
</span>
&nbsp;
=3D
&nbsp; =20
<span style=3D"white-space: nowrap; font-size:larger">
<sup>2</sup>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">&nbsp;N &nbs=
p;</span>
</span>
&nbsp;
=3D
&nbsp; N<sup>1/2</sup>
&nbsp;
=3D
&nbsp; sqrt(N)
<br> (With the exception that the radical sign <span style=3D"white-space: =
nowrap; font-size:larger">
=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>
</span> refers to the principal (positive) square root only.)
<br>
<br>
See: <a href=3D"https://www.squarerootcalculator.co/square-root-symbol.html=
"> square root symbol </a> if you need to add the symbol to a text document=
.
<br> <br>
</p>

</li>




<li>
<h4> How are square roots used: </h4>
<p> Square roots can be used:</p>
<ul>
<li>to solve for the distance between two points (Pythagorean Theorem) </li=
>
<li>to solve for the length of a side of a right triangle (Pythagorean Theo=
rem)</li>
<li>to find the solutions to quadratic equations</li>
<li>to find normal distribution</li>
<li>to find standard deviation</li>
<li>basically to solve for a squared variable in an equation</li>
</ul>
<p> If you see an equation like N<sup>2</sup> =3D 27 , you can solve for N =
by taking the square root of 27 which
gives N =3D 5.1961524 </p>=20


<br>
</li>
</ul>

